All looks alright to me, but I'd like to see what the consumer side (in mctpd) looks like before committing to this structure of EM configuration.
Waiting for https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/entity-manager/+/65666

We pushed implementation on CodeConstruct/mctp:
https://github.com/CodeConstruct/mctp/pull/17

It would be nice to get your feedback on that.

I really don't like that we have undocumented dbus interfaces now spanning even outside the OpenBMC organization.  Should we start documenting these EM config types in phosphor-dbus-interfaces?  (@edtanous - opinions?)

Yep, these should be tracked with the rest of the config structure.

Alternatively, we could make a policy that the EM config types don't leak out to other projects (or at least those we have input on), and provide a more "generic" configuration mechanism for mctpd.

> @edtanous - opinions?

The problem is that EM isn't currently capable of publishing consistent schemas to dbus.  There's some variability between a field type possibly being uintX_t, double, or a string dependent on what the config file the person actually wrote and how the macro "language" (if you can call it that) produces the result.

We could document the "idealized" interfaces, but I've been hesitant to because it would lead to people building reactors that worked on one system and quietly broke on another because of the type mismatch (I think omnisensor has this problem today).  Right now, the current state of the art is to do reactor-daemon side coercion of the parameters into the expected type.  That obviously sucks from an interface perspective, but it's what we have today.

FWIW, I've spent a little time trying to fix this in the EM code, and the problem is that EM doesn't have a direct EntityType + FieldName -> dbus type conversion table anywhere.  We could add one, but we're then going to break every downstream system that's added something manufacturer specific, or gone outside the superset of configs that's in upstream.  Whether or not it's ok to break those use cases, or if there's some kind of "fail into the old way" that's possible is probably a discussion we could have at some point.

TL; DR, I fully support anyone that want's to try to solve this, but it's a deeper problem than just not having things documented.

I'm not convinced this belongs in the Yosemite4 json file.

Sentinel Dome + all this other stuff is one possible configuration of Yv4.  It happens to be the **first** configuration.

Doesn't this belong in a Sentinel Dome JSON file?  How do we handle a different Yv4 configuration?
We will add Sentinel Dome JSON file for it. Since we have all fru data, it should be able to probe by the board fru data.

We put them into separate files.

Since we have all eeproms connected to the BMC, we should be able to split these configuration into corresponding file.

Based on a schematic, how are these determined?  I'm assuming based on them being incrementing, they really look like software-defined IDs rather than hardware defined, which would imply that they don't go into an EM config file, and would either be generated or hardcoded in the MCTP interface stack itself.

If these are BMC-wide Ids, we're going to get conflicts if we hardcode them in the config file, and someone plugs in two of the same card.
We changed this calculating by the physical bus it located.

As far as a user is concerned, does MCTP itself functionally mean anything?  I'm going to guess that this actually needs to be RDEDevice, PLDMDevice, CXLDevice, or NVMeDevice dependent on what you're implementing.  MCTP as a transport would just be assumed on those types.

Unless there are use cases that JUST involve MCTP?  My understanding of the protocol was that some other protocol had to ride on top.
We changed it to `MCTPEndpoint`.

> As far as a user is concerned, does MCTP itself functionally mean anything? 

perhaps more of long-term design decision (on what's probed and what's pre-configured), but once we know something is MCTP we can then discover the supported protocols..
ACK.  If MCTP supports discoverability then my point is moot.
Please also mention this change in commit message
Done
EndpointId looks like it's an 8 bit id?  Where would we use string?
Since we want to calculate the value by $bus, the formula is recognized as a string in JSON.

Why % 16?

i2c busses should be numbers, not strings.  remove "mctpi2c"

> Why % 16?

We have eeproms on bus 16 - 23, but our BICs are on bus 0 - 7.

> i2c busses should be numbers, not strings. remove "mctpi2c"

Done.
How is the endpointId of this device dependent on which bus it was found on?  That seems really odd that a device would know what slot it was plugged into.
Our BICs are able to know what slot it was plugged into by GPIOs. Ths `$bus % 15` result is slot index, and we do some further calculation for our EIDs mapping.
Can be either a string or a number?  That doesn't seem right to allow either or?  I don't see anywhere else where we do that?
nvm, we do that for bus.  ACK.
While I don't really like the cross-org dependency between this and CodeConstruct, it doesn't seem like we have a better option now.  Giving a +1 so forward progress can continue.

I suspect that this doesn't fully encapsulate the correct entity-json split up for this platform, given that there are CXL devices still encapsulated within another physical device, but that's up to the folks that own that platform to handle however they like.  As far as the schema is written, it looks correct.

The platform side also looks correct. 
- SD has 1 BIC.
- Each *Falls card has 1 BIC and a CXL chip.
